organismRemarks: According to Scott Ranger, Sasha was entangled in crab pot gear sometime prior to 2009 and has several scars, including one on the ridge just before her dorsal fin. This makes Sasha easily identifiable even when her flukes are not shown. She loves the South Shelter Area near Juneau. Sasha is known from the [**University of Alaska Southeast (UASE) Humpback Whale Photo ID catalog**](http://www.alaskahumpbacks.org/flukeIDcatalog.html) directed by Jan Straley.  Known to be female from genetic ID by the [**OSU Cetacean Conservation and Genomics Lab**](https://mmi.oregonstate.edu/ccgl), from the [**SPLASH study**](https://www.cascadiaresearch.org/projects/splash-structure-populations-levels-abundance-and-status-humpback-whales-north-pacific) and from observation with a calf. Mother of  Samba (2015), [**Macarena (2020)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/41376),  [**Tango (2023)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/99090) and [**Cha Cha (2025)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/138986).
taxonRemarks: Taxon recorded as "Northern bottlenose whale" by the provider

organismRemarks: Right Eye suffered a nasty ship strike leaving a large prop scar along her left flank in front of the dorsal, appears to have healed well. See a blow, go slow!  She is known as a female from observation with a calf, as mother of [**Ojito (2019-2020)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/44252) and [**Ciao (2022-2023)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/102310), and from research by [**NOAA Southwest Fisheries Science Center (SWFSC)**](https://happywhale.com/org/210).  This whale is known from research conducted by [**Cascadia Research Collective**](http://www.cascadiaresearch.org/) and collaborators

occurrenceRemarks: Photo identification; {"catalog_number":"https://happywhale.com/encounter/501842","organism_id":"(unknown)","organism_name":"(no name)","occurrence_remarks":"Picture by João Quaresma, displayed with permission"}
organismRemarks: Fran was the 2005 daughter of [**Big Fin aka River, CRC-9019**](https://happywhale.com/individual/553;enc=5630), known to be female from encounters with her 2014 calf by Whales of Guerrero and her [**2021-2022 calf Aria**](https://happywhale.com/individual/81708). She was the most popular and well known whale in California, encountered by many in Monterey Bay until her [**death from a ship strike in August of 2022**](https://www.mercurynews.com/2022/08/30/fran-was-californias-most-photographed-whale-could-her-death-have-been-prevented/). She was found in Half Moon Bay on August 29, washed up on Manhattan Beach in excellent body condition but with a broken neck.   Fran was named by [**Ferd Bergholz**](https://happywhale.com/user/63;enc=6863) in honor of his late wife, through the [**Oceanic Society**](http://www.oceanicsociety.org/). Fran often wintered in Guerrero, Mexico, documented there by Katharina Audley of the [**Whales of Guerrero Research Project**](http://www.whalesinmexico.com/). Information based on [**Cascadia Research Collective**](http://www.cascadiaresearch.org/) catalog and database including contributions by collaborating researchers.  Fran and Arias' story, and efforts to reduce ship strike risk for whales, were [**featured on CBS Sunday Morning in October 2024**](https://www.cbsnews.com/news/protecting-whales-from-ship-strikes/).
taxonRemarks: Taxon recorded as "Northern bottlenose whale" by the provider

organismRemarks: Barnacles is known as a female from genetic ID by the [**OSU Cetacean Conservation and Genomics Lab**](https://mmi.oregonstate.edu/ccgl) and the [**Juneau Flukes catalog**](http://www.juneauflukes.org/juneau-catalog.html). Noted as often staying near Juneau into the winter. Mother of [**2019 calf of Barnacles**](https://happywhale.com/individual/82140), [**Limpet (2022)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/81710) and [**Urchin (2024)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/121875).  Also known from research by [**Alaska Whale Foundation**](http://www.alaskawhalefoundation.org/). Formerly also SEAK-1337 and HW-MN0400408

organismRemarks: Flame is a known female from genetic ID by the [**OSU Cetacean Conservation and Genomics Lab**] (https://mmi.oregonstate.edu/ccgl) and as Humpback SEAK-1538 in the [**Juneau Flukes catalog**](http://www.juneauflukes.org/juneau-catalog.html). She is known to be the 2001 calf of [**SEAK-0455 Scrutineer**](https://happywhale.com/individual/35555), also confirmed by DNA sequence.   Flame is a super-mom, she has brought at least NINE calves through Juneau, AK:  - [**Blaze (2011)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/131615) - [**Spark (2013)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/80017) (Thanks Emma Luck and Suzie Teerlink for this info)  - [**Ember (2016)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/80016)  - [**Bunsen aka Flicker (2019)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/25018)  - [**Smoke (2020)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/41375)  - [**Bolt (2021)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/59902)  - [**Cinder (2022)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/81711)  - [**Sizzle (2024)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/118718) - [**Match (2025)**](https://happywhale.com/individual/139465)  Also sighted as HW-MN0400413

organismRemarks: Venom is known from the collaborative efforts of the Gulf of Maine Humpback Whale Catalog at the [**Center for Coastal Studies**](https://coastalstudies.org/humpback-whale-research/gulf-of-maine/gom-humpback-catalog/) and the North Atlantic Humpback Whale Catalog at [**Allied Whale, College of the Atlantic**](https://www.coa.edu/allied-whale/research/). organismRemarks: Motitas has been seen in both Northern and Southern California between the years 2007 – 2013. Motitas was seen in the winter breeding and calving grounds of Mexico in 2015 in a competitive group of whales in front of a group of islands called the Morros near Barra de Potosi. Motitas was named and adopted by the Cooperativa Eco Vegana de Zihuatanejo, as part of the [**Whales of Guerrero Research Project**](https://www.whalesinmexico.com/). Also formerly CRC-12256. She is known as a female from observation with a calf. Mother of [**Motitas Chiquititas**](https://happywhale.com/individual/17126), [**2020-2021 calf of Motitas**](https://happywhale.com/individual/61170) and Mother of [**2022-2023 calf of Motitas**](https://happywhale.com/individual/94379).

fieldNotes: Whale surfaced approximately 4 metres out from the rocky shore line. The whale was approximately 4+ metres in length and in around 8 metres of water depth on a high but falling tide. There were no signs of trauma or injury. There were no signs of entanglement. The wahle headed out into deeper water. The whale was recorded on the far side of the bay at 1232hrs by a local boat user. This footage was posted on Facebook by Torquay Marina. This was confirmed later by the boat owner in a conversation to me this evening. I observed the whale at 12:43hrs. I have brief video footage from my camera. which I can make available.Hopes Nose. Torquay (Torbay). 4 metres from the rocky shoreline in approximately 8 metres of water depth.

datasetName: Sea Watch Foundation Marine Megafauna Sightings: 1971 to present
fieldNotes: At first assumed this was a small minke whale or dolphin from the dorsal fin but it seems to lack a median notch in the fluke. First it breached and showed a small. curved dorsal fin in the back 3rd of the body. The back appeared dark grey with a lighter underside. Then it began tail slapping the water surface for around 5 minutes. Small pointed pectoral fins were visible. Finally spy-hopping was observed and it had a visibly light. brown/grey face and melon shaped head. The beak was short and abrupt from the domed head. A noise was heard although we are not 100% certain it was the whale. Length appeared to be around 3m. Was unsure on ID until seeing the face. but as another /same was sighted in the Sound of Mull on 25/7 it seems plausible.

fieldNotes: Clearly seen from a yacht at anchor. two Northern Bottlenose Whales patrolling up and down Loch Riddon (Ruel) close together for several hours with much leaping/breaching and tail slapping so we presumed they were hunting.  First appeared at around 16:20 on 14/09/2020 and last heard tail slapping in the dark around 04:00 15/09/2020 and not heard or seen again in the 24 hours after that at which point we left the anchorage. Photographs can be provided if required.

fieldNotes: This Northern Bottlenose Whale was named 'Gilbert' after the RNLI Lifeguard that found it on 13th Sept! The animal was subsequently observed up to 18th Sept.2009. This was a 1st for Dorset. and for Poole Bay.I. sadly. was unable to photograph him. even though I put in about 20 hours over 5 days. searching for the animal to photograph it. I failed miserably! When my wife and I observed the animal on 13th Sept. it was too distant for me to photograph it!! Typical!!
